{{One source|date=May 2018}}

The '''rundlet''' is an archaic unit-like size of [[wine]] casks once used in [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|Britain]]. It was equivalent to about 68 litres. It used to be defined as 18 ''wine gallons''—one of several gallons then in use—before the adoption of the [[imperial unit|imperial system]] in 1824, afterwards it was 15 ''imperial gallons'', which became the universal [[English unit|English base unit]] of volume in the British realm.

