{{Infobox language | name = Tjwao | altname = Tshwao | nativename = | states = [[Zimbabwe]] | speakers = <20 | date = | ref = <ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.iaaw.hu-berlin.de/de/afrika/linguistik-und-sprachen/veranstaltungen/afrikalinguistischeskolloquium/papers-wintersemester-2014-15/presentation_nyota_10_02_2015.pdf|title=Tshawo, the Endangered Language of Zimbabwe|last=|first=|date=2015|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> | familycolor = Khoisan | fam1 = [[Khoe languages|Khoe]] | fam2 = Kalahari (Tshu–Khwe) | fam3 = East | fam4 = [[Tshwa language|Tsoa]] | dia1 = | dia2 = | dia3 = | nation = {{Flag|Zimbabwe}} (as "Koisan") | lc1 = | ld1 = | lc2 = | ld2 = | notice = | glotto = | glottorefname = |isoexception=dialect }}
'''Tjwao''' (formerly Tshwao) is an endangered [[Khoe languages|Khoe language]] spoken by fewer than 20 people in the [[Tsholotsho District]] of [[Zimbabwe]], all over 60 years of age.<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.channelzim.net/home/16-featured/4131-khosian-tshwao-language-in-near-extinction|title=Khosian Tshwao language in near extinction|last=Dialogue|first=Radio|access-date=2017-06-16|language=en-gb}}</ref>{{Dead link|date=March 2018|fix-attempted=yes}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.southerneye.co.zw/2014/05/14/daunting-task-crafting-san-language-syllabus/|title=Daunting task in crafting San language syllabus|date=2014-05-14|website=Southern Eye|access-date=2017-06-16}}</ref> A slightly larger group of 100 have passive or partial knowledge of the language.
It is the only [[Khoisan language]] in Zimbabwe, where "Koisan" is an officially recognised language in the constitution.
Tjwao belongs to the [[Tshwa language|Tshwa]] (Tsoa-Kua) cluster of East Kalahari Khoe languages. It is very similar to the varieties of [[Ganade language|Ganade]] noted by Westphal and Traill. Although mentioned by scholars for several decades, documentation of the language only began in 2012.
